The article is a message from President Barack Obama to the Congress, transmitting a proposed Agreement for Cooperation between the United States and Vietnam on the Peaceful Uses of Nuclear Energy. The agreement is in accordance with the Atomic Energy Act of 1954 and aims to advance the nonproliferation and foreign policy interests of the United States. Vietnam has committed to relying on the international market for nuclear fuel supply and is prohibited from enriching or reprocessing U.S.-origin material without U.S. consent. The agreement has an initial term of 30 years, with the option for termination by either party. The proposed agreement permits the transfer of information, material, equipment, and components for nuclear research and power production, but not Restricted Data or sensitive nuclear technology. Vietnam is a non-nuclear-weapon state party to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and has comprehensive safeguards agreements in place. The President has considered the views and recommendations of relevant departments and agencies and has approved the agreement, urging Congress to give it favorable consideration. The President's administration is prepared to begin consultations with the Senate Foreign Relations Committee and the House Foreign Affairs Committee.